SEM: standard error of the mean, SR: National Nutrient Database for Standard Reference

1The changes in nutrient values may reflect reformulations in products, changes in the market shares of brands, or more accurate data. Examples of more accurate data include analytical data, market share data, and data from a nationally representative sample.
2 This five-digit number uniquely identifies a food item in USDA’s National Nutrient Database for Standard Reference (SR).

3For many food items N=0 and range and SEM are not available as they have not been analyzed. For foods that have been analyzed, most saturated fat and some total sugar values are determined by summing individual saturated fatty acids and individual sugars, respectively; hence n = 0 and SEM are not available.
4Percent change is calculated using the formula: ((Re-sampled Nutrient Value - Baseline Nutrient Value)/Baseline Nutrient Value) * 100.
